'''Multivesicular release''' (MVR) is the phenomenon by which individual [[chemical synapse]]s, forming the junction between [[neuron]]s, is mediated by multiple [[active zone#Vesicle pool|releasable vesicles]] of [[neurotransmitter]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tong|first1=G|last2=Jahr|first2=CE|title=Multivesicular release from excitatory synapses of cultured hippocampal neurons.|journal=Neuron|date=January 1994|volume=12|issue=1|pages=51–9|pmid=7507341|doi=10.1016/0896-6273(94)90151-1}}</ref> In [[neuroscience]], it is a subject of debate whether one or many vesicles are released per [[action potential]].<ref name="christie">{{cite journal|last1=Christie|first1=JM|last2=Jahr|first2=CE|title=Multivesicular release at Schaffer collateral-CA1 hippocampal synapses.|journal=The Journal of Neuroscience|date=4 January 2006|volume=26|issue=1|pages=210–6|pmid=16399689|doi=10.1523/jneurosci.4307-05.2006|pmc=2670931}}</ref>
==Examples==
In the mammalian brain, MVR has been shown to be common in CA1 [[pyramidal cell]]s and [[Schaffer collateral]] cells.<ref name="christie" /> It has also been proposed<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Glowatzki|first1=E|last2=Fuchs|first2=PA|title=Transmitter release at the hair cell ribbon synapse.|journal=Nature Neuroscience|date=February 2002|volume=5|issue=2|pages=147–54|pmid=11802170|doi=10.1038/nn796}}</ref> and then refuted<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Chapochnikov NM, Takago H, Huang CH, Pangršič T, Khimich D, Neef J, Auge E, Göttfert F, Hell SW, Wichmann C, Wolf F, Moser T |title=Uniquantal release through a dynamic fusion pore is a candidate mechanism of hair cell exocytosis |journal=Neuron |volume=83 |issue=6 |pages=1389–403 |year=2014 |pmid=25199706 |doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.08.003 |url=}}</ref> at the [[ribbon synapse]]s formed between [[inner hair cell]] and [[spiral ganglion]] neurons.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fuchs|first1=PA|title=Time and intensity coding at the hair cell's ribbon synapse.|journal=The Journal of Physiology|date=1 July 2005|volume=566|issue=Pt 1|pages=7–12|pmid=15845587|doi=10.1113/jphysiol.2004.082214|pmc=1464726}}</ref> Recent evidence points to a possibility of MVR at neocortical connections of the [[somatosensory cortex]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Huang|first1=CH|last2=Bao|first2=J|last3=Sakaba|first3=T|title=Multivesicular release differentiates the reliability of synaptic transmission between the visual cortex and the somatosensory cortex.|journal=The Journal of Neuroscience|date=8 September 2010|volume=30|issue=36|pages=11994–2004|pmid=20826663|doi=10.1523/jneurosci.2381-10.2010}}</ref>
